HAZARDOUS RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO LEAKER.  UPON ARRIVAL RESPONDER ACKNOWNLEDGED THAT DAMAGED PACKAGE WAS A CORROSIVE.  USING DECISON TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET, RESPONDER THEN PUT ON GOGGLES, BOOTS, APRON AND SILVER SHIELD GLOVES. RESPONDER THEN APPLIED SODIUM BICARBONATE ON SPILL, TESTED AND ACID FELL WITHIN 6-9 (BLUE) NEUTRAL RANGE.  THE RESPONDER CLEANED THE AREA AND TOOK DAMAGED PACKAGE TO DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.CAPS SHOULD BE SECURELY TIGHTENED ON THE PLASTIC BOTTLES.

column168: May 8, 2009: At approximately 7:15PM, conductor noted tank car GATX 30404, load,   2-Diethylaminoethanol (Class 8 (3), UN 2686, PG II) with a small steady drip originating from the bottom outlet closure cap, when car was in Conrail's River Rouge, MI yard.  Car was shipped from local industry, Taminco, Inc., Riverview, MI.      Conrail's A. Richter, Risk Manager, contacted emergency response contractor Eagle Construction, Findlay, OH, to respond due to unavailable response from the shipper.  CR Trainmaster P. Cassettee had the car moved to isolation in the yard's R.I.P. track in the Car Shop area.  Eagle Construction responders arrived at approximately 11pm and inspected the car.    Drip originating from the top of the 4" bottom outlet valve closure cap.  Examination of operating handle at bottom of car appeared to be in the closed position and was pinned and sealed.  Attempt to slowly remove bottom outlet cap to examine the bottom outlet cap's gasket was stopped due to steady flow of product noted.  Cap resecured tool tight, outlet area wiped down, and valve was watched for a period of approximately 15 minutes, with no further leakage noted.  Leak deemed secure at approximately 11:50pm.    As the bottom outlet valve closure cap's gasket and valve could not be examined during this response, to determine condition or presence (of gasket, or actual valve open/closure), the car is to be returned to the shipping facility for their internal inspection and/or repair.

column168: Initial Report  According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  During a routine inspection of the trailer, a leak was discovered.  SET Environmental of Bridgeview, Illinois was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, a drip bucket had been placed at the back of the trailer, to catch any runoff of free product.  The free liquid was contained inside the trailer, and did not reach the ground surface beneath the trailer, or impact the environment.  Upon inspection of the freight, two (2) 375-gallon totes were discovered damaged.  One (1) - due to a welded seam along top of tote, and one (1) - was a failure to the outlet valve at bottom of tote.  Upon offloading the totes into two (2) 330-gallon totes, no free product remained.  Therefore, it is assumed that no more than 50 gallons released.  Again, all free product was contained to the trailer.  One (1) 55-gallon drum of absorbent pads and PPE was generated during the cleanup, trailer was offloaded into a new trailer provided by TCS, and remaining freight was sent on.  Damaged totes and two (2) 330-gallon totes were brought to SET's facility in Glenwood, pending disposition, and return to shipper.  There were no injuries or exposures reported. column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a welded seam failure, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Triple Crown Services will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Missing Component or Device
column168: While checking his load prior to entering the Clean Harbors Burton MI facility, the driver noticed a small leak coming from rear flange of the tanker.  The appropriate persons were notified and the emergency response team responded to the problem.  They donned the appropriate PPE and shoveled the contaminated dirt and gravel into a 5 gallon pail from this spill location and another nearby where the unit had been parked.  The pail was re manifested to a disposal site in El Dorado AR.  The tanker was repaired as it was found that a barely visible bolt was missing from the flange, causing the leak.  The missing bolt was replaced, all bolts properly tightened and the load continued to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: Driver was instructed to perform a more thorough pretrip inspection and the maintenance shop was notified of the situation so that they could begin a check of all similar less visible bolts.

column168: A tanker arrived at the customer's site to pick up a load.  When pumping began, an internal valve on the tanker failed and caused a back flow of the material to spill onto the ground.  The driver immediately shut down the unit and the facilitiy's internal emergency response team was activated.  Upon arrival at the scene, the first responders contained all free liquid with a suitable absorbent material and placed this in a suitable UN rated container for transportation and disposal.  In addition, the surface onto which the material was released was cleaned and all clean-up debris was placed in the same container.  All debris generated as a result of this incident was palced into storage pending off-site transportation and disposal.  At the conclusion of the clean-up activity, the vehicle was removed from the site for inspection and any necessary repairs. The tanker returned empty to the facility for repairs.      Please note that the intent of this shipment was to transport a hazardous waste for disposal at a licensed hazardous waste management facility.  As the incident occured at the initiation of the loading process, a shipping paper was not generated as the truck was placed out of service in order to address the faulty valve.  No product was transported from the site.
column169: At the time the tank was dispatched to this job site, all inspections were reviewed and were within the requred inspection intervals and there was no documented issues associated with the tank or its valve system.  At thie time of the incident, the driver took all necceesary steps t minimize the potential impact of the release and immedialtey notified the appropriate individuals as to the situation at hand.    In order to prevnt a recurrence, drivers will continue to conduct thorough pre and post trip inspections and will take all appropriate measures should a damaged, defective or inoperable device be found prior to or during operation.

column168: A box truck containing a shipment of drums arrived at the 10 day storage facility.  All but 3 of the drums were offloaded, processed and palletized for shipment to the intended waste disposal facility.  The 3 drums were left overnight on the truck as there were not enough to complete a pallet.  When the drum was moved the next day, a residue was noticed underneath the drum, on the floor of the box truck.  Emergency response personnel donned the appropriate PPE and overpacked the leaking drum into a suitable salvage drum.  The spilled material was cleaned up and the truck was cleaned with a suitable cleaning compound.  The spilled material and absorbent rags were also placed in the salvage drum and it was loaded on a trailer to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: Drivers were cautioned to check carefully when accepting old used drums of material.

column168: A tanker trailer picked up a load and drove to a truck stop to scale the load.  Upon arrival, the driver conducted a load check and noticed moisture around two of the dome lids.  The appropriate personnel were notified and an emergency response crew and mechanic were dispatched to the scene.  The crew donned the appropriate PPE and cleaned up the moisture with absorbant pads, which were placed into a suitable 5 gallon salvage pail.  The mechanic replaced the dome lid gaskets and the vehicle proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The maintenance shop will check the dome lid gaskets on tankers more frequently to prevent recurrance.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: A shipment of 3-1 cubic yard boxes was picked up and brought to the intended 10 day storage facility for processing and loading to the intended waste disposal facility.  When it was unloaded onto the dock, it was observed that one of the three cubic yard boxes was not in condition for further transport as it appeared to have been stored outside in the weather and it's condition had deteriorated.  Arrangements were made with the emergency response crew to repack the box into a suitable salvage container.  Prior to their arrival, it was noticed that material began leaking from the box onto the dock floor.  The LA State police hazardous incident hotline was called and report number 09-02356 was assigned.  The response crew arrived, donned the appropriate PPE and repacked the box into a new cubic yard box and pallet along with the material used to contain and absorb the spilled material.  The shipment then was loaded to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The driver that picked up the shipment was reprimanded for picking up a shipment that was not in proper condition for transportation.  Additional training for this driver and all others at this location will be conducted reviewing proper condition of shipments for pickup.  The shipper was also notified and informed that containers in this condition will no longer be accepted for shipment.

column168: On 5/1/09 container, HRZU433325-2/TX2130033, was tendered to ocean carrier in Houston for loading to the Horizon Discovery, DI568S. The vessel sailed 5/2/09 and arrived in San Juam 5/7/09. Container was released/pick-up by the shipper on 5/8/09. Once the container reached the port gate, 0940hrs, it was observed to have droplets coming from the under carriage. Consignee was consulted and it was decided to have it continue to their facility, about 1 mile away, to be addressed.    Consignee discharged the container and discovered that one of 32 drums of cyclohexanone, (UN1915/Class 3), had a pin hole leak at the bottom chim/rim. It was estimated 20 gallons of product had leaked out onto the container floor. Arrangements were made to contain and clean-up.    Leak was attributed to a failure in the drum integrity, pin hole. There was no apparent rubbing or impact on the drum to cause the pin hole.
column169: Shipper should review their loading procedures to make sure drum inspections are made prior to loading, while loading product, and then again while loading/securing into the container to make sure no future leaking drums are shipped.

column168: SHIPPER IS UNDER AN AUDIT FOR SHIPPING UNDECLARED HAZ MATS IN OUR SYSTEM. I WAS DOING A CHECK ON THE BOXES THAT CAME IN FROM THE DRIVER AND I HAD TO REQUEST AN MSDS FOR BOTH THE ITEMS THAT SAID FLAMMABLE ON THE BACK OF THEIR BOTTLES. THERE ARE 3BOTTLES OF THE UN2811 HAZARD CLASS 6.1 AND ONE BOTTLE OF UN 1219 HAZARD CLASS 3. BOTH ARE PACKING GROUP II. ONE IS SPECIAL PERMITAND I BELIEVE THAT IT WAS THE UN2811. ALL FOUR OF THE UNDECLAREDS ARE 5 LITERS EACH. PKGS ARE BEING HELD IN PAUCITY FOR CUSTOMER PICK UP.

The shipper tendered container, MSKU458609-2/CA2079121, to ocean carrier on 5/6/09 in Tacoma for loading to the Horizon Anchorage, AZ752N, for transit to Anchorage. Vessel departed 5/7/09 and arrived in Anchorage 5/10/09. During a random inspection it was discovered the shipper had failed to declare UN1075/Class 2.1, and the labels were wrong showing "Flammable Liquid", instead of "Flammable Gas". Pertinent parties were notified for corrective action.
column169: Shipper must review their shipments prior to tendering to the trucker and the ocean carrier to make sure all hazardous commodities are captured and the paperwork reflects the same. They should review each commodity for correct labels.
column172: Cylindrical metal container, not for compressed gases (i. e., not a pressure vessel)

column168: Paint was being loaded when pallet broke, causing forklift blade to puncture paint pail.  Absorbent and PPE was used to clean the spill.
column169: Using better constructed pallets to transport fragile material will help in the future.

column168: The freight was docked for loading onto a city van.  This drum was the last piece placed on the van.  It is unknown who loaded the drum.  The smell of paint was noticed by a driver and then the punctured drum was found in trailer 641-6006.  Spilled product has been recouped and is in NNA's OS&D bay.

column168: A BNSF switch crew observed and reported UTLX 667926 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from the top fitting area of this tank car during normal switching operations in the railyard. UTLX 667926 was isolated in the railyard awaiting further inspection from a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder. The BNSF responder reported finding all six manway securement bolts loose. The manway gasket was also inspected and cleaned by the responder. Afterwards, the manway lid was closed and all securement bolts were properly tool tightened by 1230 hrs. CDT, 5/15/09. No ground impact from spillage was evident. All spillage atop and on the side shell of UTLX 667926 evaporated. No further product release was observed from subsequent rail movements of UTLX 667926.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: GATX 37340 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard was reported with a white crystalline build-up around its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area. GATX 37340 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard with a catch receptacle placed under the BOV. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was called to inspect GATX 37340. After the responder knocked-off the crystalline build-up into the receptacle, inspection of the bottom operated BOV commenced. The responder reported finding the BOV operating handle pinned and in the closed position. The bottom outlet cap (BOC) was found two full turns loose. The BOC was removed to inspect and clean the BOC gasket. After the BOC was removed, the responder noticed a small residue product drip emanating from the closed ball valve. The responder replaced the BOC and tool tightened it which stopped any further product release by 0600 hrs. MDT, 5/15/09. No ground impact from this product release was evident. The product spillage captured in the receptacle was earmarked for proper disposal. GATX 37340 was redirected to a qualified repair facility for detailed inspection and warranted repairs to the BOV.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: An outbound BNSF train inspection in the railyard revealed entrained UTLX 670992 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with a white crystalline build-up around its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders were called and immediately inspected UTLX 670992. The responders noted that UTLX 670992 had no seals applied to any of the fittings. After the responders wiped the crystalline build-up around the BOV, inspection of the bottom operated BOV commenced. The responders reported finding the BOV operating handle not pinned or sealed and in an open position. The bottom outlet closure cap (BOC) was not tool tight. The BOV flange connection to the tank car had all four flange bolts in a hand tight condition. The responders closed the BOV, pinned and sealed the operating handle (BNSF seal numbered 06157294 applied). The BOV closure cap was tool tightened along with the loose BOV flange bolts. No further residue product release was noted after the BOV securement was completed. In addition, the responders inspected the top fitting area for securement. Five of the eight manway securement bolts were found to be less than tool tight (four of these were finger loose) and these were properly tool tightened. Afterwards, BNSF seal numbered 061257145 was applied to the manway cover. The liquid line closure plugs were also found loose and these were tool tightened. BNSF seal numbered 06157147 was applied to the valve housing cover securement pin. Securement of entrained UTLX 670992 was completed by 1440 hrs. PDT, 5/15/09. The small amount of ground spillage under the unsecured BOV was scooped-up and placed inside a portable receptacle for future appropriate disposal.
column169: Ensure the shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On May 8, 2009 at 12:05 hours, personnel in the CSXT Transflo Yard in East Chicago, IN discovered UTLX130295, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2009-05-08-00098). Sunpro Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 2 bolts on the fill hole to be loose.  Sunpro personnel tightened the bolts and the leak stopped.  The car was decontaminated and released to destination. This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code:  224  NARRI: 5 (5+5+0) X (2+0) = 100
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On May 15th at 11:28 hours, personnel in the CSXT Bostic yard discovered GATX200245, a loaded tank car of Combustible Liquid, N.O.S. leaking from the top of car.  The car was isolated and Chemtrec (Report number 2009-0513-00110) assisted in contacting the shipper, Magellan Midstream Partners LP.  Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the cause of the release was due to a missing manway cover gasket.  Hepaco representatives replaced the gasket, properly tightened the securement bolts/nuts with a wrench, and the leak stopped  The rail car was decontaminated and then released on to destination.    An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not completed for this incident.  Note: This incident did not require a special shipping move.    Cause Code:  207  NARRI:  5 (5+1+0) X (2+0) = 60
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On May 13, 2009 at 12:00pm CSXT hazardous material personnel in the CSXT Moncrief Yard discovered UTLX 58891, a loaded tank car of Combustible Liquid, N.O.S. (Terpene Residue) leaking from around the manway cover. The car was isolated and the shipper, IFF Chemical Holdings, Inc was notified directly. CSXT hazardous materials managers E.G. Cook, M.A. Mullis and director, M.D. Lunsford found the manway cover gasket and the manway nozzle had product residue caked on their surfaces so as to prevent a good liquid tight seal. The manway cover gasket and the manway nozzle were cleaned of residue and the manway cover was secured wrench tight. The car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.            Cause Code:  208  Narri: 5(5+1+0) X (2+0) = 60
column169: No additional comments.

column168: The BNSF Terminal Trainmaster reported IAPX 1053 (DOT 113A90W tank car) continuously venting product with piping frosted in the railyard. IAPX 1053 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting a detailed inspection from a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder. The responder reported that a vent pipe coupling nut had become disconnected at a pipe joint leaving a small gap in the piping. This opening allowed the gaseous product to escape at this location rather than at the top of the vent pipe during acceptable venting events. The responder refastened the coupling nut which ended further product venting at this pipe joint by 0600 hrs. PDT, 5/18/09.

column168: On May 15, 2009, while being switched at KCS' Jackson, Mississippi classification rail yard, GATX 59472 was discovered leaking from the top portion of the tank car.  The tank car was immediately switched to an isolation track to prevent further movement and spillage and to facilitate safe emergency response activity.  KCS mobilized United States Environmental Services (USES), of Jackson, MS for investigation, mitigation and remediation.  The emergency responder found a loose connection where the liquid valve (ball type valve) connects to the flange plate on the tank car. Responders reports 1/2 turn secured the the valve connection and mitigated the elease. The spilled material was remediated by USES.

column168: The cargo tank was loaded at rack at the shipper.  The driver is not allowed on top of the cargo tank at this plant.  When he got to the guard shack to check out, they noticed product leaking down from drain tube from spill dam on top of the cargo tank.  They had the driver pull over.   They put a spill pad up the drain hose to prevent more product from dripping down and had the driver go back to the loading rack where they could check the top to see what was causing the leak.   The dome lid collar seemed to be out of adjustment.  They changed out the gasket, readjusted the dome cover on the collar and used rubber mallets to pound it tight.  They drove around to make sure it was tight and there was no further leakage.   The spill was cleaned up with spill pads.
column169: After the load was completed and the trailer was washed, the cargo tank was inspected at our shop to make sure there was no damage to the manhole collar and it was not out of round.  The shop found no sign of damage.  They replaced the gasket, pressurized the trailer to check for leaks and found none.

column168: Driver was about 60 miles from the shipper and pulled into a truckstop  When he got out, he noticed some product drips on the top area of the cargo tank coming from the rear washout cap.  Washout cap was tight.  We got permission to break the seal on the washout cap to check it out.   Driver replaced the gasket in the washout cap with an extra white gasket he was given when the trailer was prepped.  He also did the front washout cap.  He said it looked like there may have been some product moisture there too but not very noticeable. He replaced it to be on the safe side.   He drove around a bit and the replacement gaskets appear to have solved the problem.  Driver was able to use a spill pad to wipe the drips off the side of the trailer.
column169: We have to be extra careful when putting the gaskets in the dome and washout caps especially with this product or it will find a way to seep out. Driver needs to carry extra gaskets and keep an eye on it.

column168: GAPX 9039 was involved in an overspeed coupling incident which resulted in tank shell damage which allowed material to escape.  The car was isolated and the shipper notified. The original incident which resulted in the damage occurred at 06:58 on May 22, 2009.  The leak from GAPX 9039 was not discovered until 13:43, May 26, 2009, when a small drip was noticed by carrier personnel after the car had been moved, along several other cars, to an adjacent rail yard .  This car had been inspected and no release detected at the time of the original incident.  There was no external sign of damage to this car.       An environmental contractor, Hepaco, Inc., responded and transferred the remaining material into another rail tank car for further handling.  All released material was cleaned-up, neutralized and properly disposed of.      The car was cleaned and purged and will be moved to a tank car shop for futher inspection to determine the exact cause of the release and the extent of damage.     Two contractor employees received a minor chemical burn to the skin on their shoulder when some of the material was splashed onto their protective suits while attempting to patch the leak.  The material entered the suit through a seam.  The two were treated with a topical cream and released from a local clinic.  No lost time due to the exposure.

column168: The shipment was originally booked with two (2) items of hazardous materials:    -UN2320, Tetraethylenepentamine, Class 8, PG III  -UN3351, Pyrethroid Pesticide, Liquid, Toxic, Flammable (Bifenthrin, Xylene),   Class 6.1 (3), PG III, FP 42C, Marine Pollutant    For loading on the Hapag-Lloyd Container Line vessel Santos Express from Houston to Buenos Aires, Argentina.    The shipper advised Hapag-Lloyd a day prior to the vessel arriving in Buenos Aires of additional hazardous material (UN2911, Radioactive Material, Excepted Package - Articles, Class 7, (CS-137) in the container that was not originally booked or otherwise identified. Our driver picked up a loaded trailer filled with Acrylamide Solution at the SNF, Inc.  Driver physically checked the dome lid to insure proper closure, but failed to check the clean out caps causing a spill to the ground when the driver pulled out of the shippers yard.
column169: Our driver was counseled on what is expected of a proper pre-trip inspection.  Had the pre-trip been performed properly and thoroughly, this incident could have been prevented.  In the future, an incident such as this will be used as an example during training of what could happen when a pre-trip is not performed properly or thoroughly.

column168: At approximately 10:15 am a white residue trail was observed on the concrete and asphalt located at the south entrance of our yard.  The residue looked like dry caustic soda.  I walked east toward the south entrance of our facility and the white residue trail continued though it was less noticeable.  I was trying to decipher if the trail led in to our facility or led out of our facility; based on the spotting on the pavement it was determined it was clear to me that this had to be a bulk load of caustic soda that departed from our facility around 4:20 am.   I called our Bulk Driver to find out if he noticed anything peculiar with his delivery.  He mentioned that as he was attempting to unload at the customer the trailer was not building air pressure required to unload the product.  He heard an air leak coming from the top of the trailer.  Upon investigating this air leak he found air escaping from a small section on the 20” man way seal.  He attempted to tighten the closure, but they were already tight.  He shut off the air, bled the remaining air pressure, and then proceeded to loosen the fasteners that secure the dome lid in the closed position.  When the air pressure in the tanker was neutral he opened the 20” man way and found the gasket had been pinched and it had not seated properly.
column169: Based on our best estimate there is less than two gallons of product that was released.  I cleaned and neutralized with a 0.3% solution of Phosphoric acid and Water; applying the solution on the dry residual with a small (2 gallon) pressurized bottle sprayer.  There are no injuries.  There is no property damage.    There is a small section on the gasket that came out of the channel located in the lid; when the operator finished loading the trailer and closed the lid the gasket did not seat properly.  The dome securement devices were tightened and checked, however the pinched gasket was not evident.  The gasket was replaced in the dome lid.    The material handlers that load these trailers are involved in closing these dome lids; as one of their checks prior to closing the lids they are to visually inspect the gasket and ensure it is seated in the channel prior to closing the lid.    Another corrective action is the addition of a drain ball valve.  The tanker has a spill way at the top of the trailer (a rectangular elevated parameter around the manway) and at the back corners of the spill way are drains.  Attached to these drains are hoses to help direct rinse water or residue down to the bottom of the trailer.  There are two "drains", one on each side of the trailer and they are joined at the bottom of the trailer and joined by a "T" fitting.  There is now a ball valve that has been added at the bottom of this Tee.  The ball valve is to be closed while in trailer is in transit.

column17: Interstate Company of North America, LLC
column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While making a delivery at Carmeuse, the tank overflowed, which resulted in the release of approximately 150 gallons of flammable liquid, nos.  The free product released to the gravel surface beneath the above ground storage tank at the facility.  Lewis Environmental Group of Royersford, Pennsylvania was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, Lewis Environmental Group applied absorbent material, oil dry, and sand to the affected area.  A vacuum truck was utilized to recover the free liquid and water, which had pooled on the ground surface surrounding the tank.  Lewis Environmental Group proceeded to excavate the impacted gravel/soil mixture, which was containerized into one (1) rolloff box, along with the spent absorbents, oil dry, and sand.  One (1) 55-gallon drum of cleanup debris/sludge was also generated during the cleanup.  Disposal will be coordinated by Lewis Environmental Group in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a faulty gauge on the tank, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Interstate Company of North America, LLC will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: A vehicle transporting hazardous waste was en route between the point of generation and the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at an in transit storage facility pending continuing transportation.  While at this storage facility, an inspection discovered that a small amount of material had escaped from the trailer onto the parking area where the trailer was staged.  Facility personnel immediately activated the facilities’ emergency response plan and a crew was assembled to respond to the release.  IN addition, the California Department of Toxic Substance Control was notified as a courtesy but was not reportable under their rules.      Upon arrival, the response crew, utilizing appropriate personnel protective equipment entered the trailer to identify the source of the release.  Once found it was discovered that a combination package containing a 5 gallon container of a mixed acid waste was packaged within a carbon steel UN rated container.  During the course of transportation, it is believed that the inner container cracked allowing the acidic waste material to interact with the carbon steel outer container.  It is believed that the material degraded the steel and allowed approximately ½ gallon of material to escape to the floor of the van trailer and the surface upon which the vehicle was staged.  The emergency response crew re containerized the leaking container into a suitable, compatible salvage container and proceeded to decontaminate and recover all material released.  This clean-up debris was containerized and was disposed of, along with the original container at the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the driver arrived at the loading facility to accept the container in question for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the profile established to qualify this waste stream was suspended until such time as the shipper was advised on the situation and determined what steps could be taken to preclude a repeat occurrence.  In addition, our driver has been re instructed to ensure a thorough container inspection be performed on each container in order to identify any containers demonstrating conditions that could question the integrity of the container

column168: A vehicle transporting hazardous waste was en route between the point of generation and the intended waste management facility. If a suspect container is identifed, an appropriate action such as the use of a salvage drum or transfer of the material to a new container is to be done before accepting for transportation.

column168: On May 21, 2009 at 09:04 hrs, personnel in the CSXT Queensgate Yard, discovered CMHX 247517, a loaded covered hopper car of Ammonia Nitrate, solids, leaking from the side and bottom of car. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2009-05-21-00077).  Eagle Construction, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the product was leaking from behind a small hole or opening behind a reinforcement rib.  Eagle personnel plugged the bottom of the rib with expandable foam and materials and the leak stopped.  Eagle representatives cleaned up the spill material and the car was released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On May 27, 2009 at 10:30 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Connersville Yard discovered GATX 90482, a residue tank car of HEXAMETHYLENEDIAMINE, SOLID possibly leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and shipper and consignee were notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2009-05-27-00236). Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found no evidence of a leak. Later in the afternoon, CSXT employees complained of inhalation aggravation from possible chemical exposure, and the CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager responded to the scene. Upon investigation, it was noted that some crystallized material was present around the wash out flange on the bottom of the car which was obscured by a fabricated plate and insulation between the saddles. There was no obvious or current excursion from the car, but the bolts and flange had crystalline product indicating when the product is heated, that some release may occur during the loading and unloading process and not while in a solid state. The shipper is obtaining a FRA movement approval and the car will be released back to transportation. This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code:  641  NARRI:  2(4+3+0) X (2+0) = 28

column168: The incident occurred on 5/09/09 at approximately 18:30. Train #107 south bound with an estimated speed of 45 mph derailed at MP 60.5 between latitude N29 33' 59.5" longitude W8117' 5.7" and N29 33' 58.1" longitude W8117' 6.0". The reason for the derailment is under investigation.The result of the derailment caused a hazardous material released to the environment. Rail tanker TILX 110210 laded with 17,800 gallons of hydrochloric acid at 38% concentration was punctured on the lower BL corner. The hole was approximately 6"x 6". The release of acid to the environment was estimated at 16,800 gallons. The acid soaked into the surrounding soils by the rail car and in a naturally occurring depressed low laying area. The remaining acid was salvaged and sold to Sun Belt Chemicals.The package failure was a heavy impact from another rail car striking the lower B left end of the tank car and puncturing a 6"x6" hole in the shell. The duration for the release was estimated at 6 to 18 hours. The first responders (Flagler County, St. Johns County (lead), and Duval established control of isolation, observation, and no evacuation. The first responders made attempts to control the leak and were deterred by heavy vegetation and the position of the acid car in the matrix of derailed cars. The second attempt was made by SWS Environmental (FEC Railway's Emergency Contractor) and the counties first responders the morning of May 10th. At this point, it was determined that a significant released occurred. The final ER and remedial actions followed with assistance from FDEP and the USEPA. The site was secured for corrective action on Monday 5/11/09 < > 8:00.

column168: The shipment was two plastic drums, stretch wrapped to a wooden skid. During transport to the FedEx ramp from the shipper's dock, the freight shifted, partially tearing away from the skid. In doing so, the Corrosive labels on the drums were revealed. When the drums were placed on the skid, the labels were facing each other. I spoke to Joe Sullivan from the shipper. He indicated a temporary employee prepared the shipment and may have been unaware of the nature of the contents and it's requirement to offer by air. Typically these shipments travel by FedEx Freight, properly offered. As it was there was no markings, labeling, shipping papers, emergency response information or other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. The FAA was notified, I spoke to Hazmat Mgr Kate Zamparelli in BOS. The freight is being held pending an FAA. inspection.

column168: The box was found leaking. The box was opened to reveal a blue, plastic recycling wastepaper basket that held three glass jars. The jars originally contained pickles, as the labels were still on the jars. The screw on caps were held in placewith duct tape. The jars were wrapped in bubblewrap, and surrounded with more bubble wrap to cover the dunnage. The was no evidence of any absorbent material inthe package. When we opened the box we found two of the jars laying in an other than upright position. One of the jars had broken, allowing the contents to escape.The gasoline ate through the plastic basket, through the fibreboard box and contaminated several other packages, including a laptop. There were no markings,labeling, orientation arrows, shipping papers, emergency response information no rother indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. I spoke to theshipper, a fleet maintenance manager, who initially indicated he did not know that gasoline was flammable. When challenged he admitted knowing gasoline was flammable.The shipper was of the beief that FedEx had caused this spill and was therefore not at fault. The FAA was notified, I spoke to SA Kenneth Clark. The freight was held pending an FAA inspection. The freight was subsequently released to the recipient.

column168: Driver was on Highway A and got off a little too far on the right side of the road where there is no real shoulder to speak of.  The ground was soft and vehicle was pulled off of the road. There has been about 11 inches of rain in the area. EE did not try to get back on the road.  There was a big culvert located where the vehicle left the road.  The vehicle caught the culvert and starting rolling off to on the Right side of the shoulder into a ditch.  The vehicle rolled over 2-3 times.    Highway patrol responded.  There was no release of propane but parts on the lading retention system were bent.
column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

Entrained EXFU 51489 and USPU 455062 (imported shipments in 20 foot IM101 tank containers) that arrived earlier on an inbound BNSF train at the intermodal strip tracks were reported by BNSF mechanical personnel emanating a product odor. Inspection of these containers by BNSF contract responders revealed no leak source. A nearby entrained like tank container UTCU 454362 (import shipment in 20 foot IM101 tank container) was identified as the odor source. Responders found a small amount of product that had accumulated at the bottom end of this container towards the valve end at a bolted support bracket. A tank breach was suspected since it appeared that product had migrated downward from the top of a welded stiffener ring that circumferences this tank container. Later, a stress corrosion crack at a weld seem at the top portion of the welded stiffener ring was identified at the leak source. All spillage that did not evaporate was wiped. UTCU 454362 was carefully moved and isolated at the intermodal facility's containment area. The product in UTCU 454362 was successfully transferred without further incident to another tank container on 5/08/09. The non-leaking residue UTCU 454362 was out-gated and forwarded to an appropriate tank container repair facility.

column168: CN switch crew reported a strong odor coming from tank car WCHX 23121 R/ LAST CONTAINED FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. (PULP MILL LIQUID) during switching operations at the CN Markham Yard, East Hazel Crest, IL. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN response team responded noting the bottom outlet valve handle pin out and the valve open approximately 1/4 turn, the bottom outlet cap was in place, but an odor was noted. Valve closed and handle secured. Further inspection noted the same odor coming from the manway nozzel, four of six manway cover bolts were found less than tool tight. Once both closures were secured, odor dissipated and the tank car was released for movement.

column168: The checker Louis Guglielmetti was using a forklift with short forks on a skid that should have been moved with long forks. column168: HAZMAT shipment was being loaded onto truck. The forklift driver made an error and he hit one of the drums with his forklift blade and punctured the drum near the middle of the drum. Approx. 15L of hazmat, flammable liquid, leaked out of the drum and onto the loading dock area. The area was segregated, and 2 supervisors cleaned up area with absorbant pads and stored the clean up material and damaged drum into a recovery drum. The consignee Minitube accepted the recovery drum with the rest of the shipment. The local FAA was advised.The accident was a result of a forklift error, not from any defect with the drum.    Corrective action on the part of the handling agent , Menzies Aviation, was to double skid hazmat shipments and use a pallet-jack, instead of a forklift, whenver possible. In addition the forklift driver was instructed to use greater care with the forklift , especially in regards to hazmat.
column169: The handling agent, Menzies Aviation, made the following corrective actions :   1. Use double skids to store import hazmat.   2. Use shrinkwrap to secure import hazmat to the skid.   3. Use of pallet-jack ,instead of forklift, whenever possible when moving skids of hazmat.

column168: Train crew notified Trainmaster Brashear that they smelled an odor coming from tank car CELX 1202 at approximately 0430 hrs. The trainmaster arrived on scene and could not detect an odor. Brashear notified the shipper BASF and was put in touch with a representative from Celanese that could check the car for problems at approximately 0500 hrs. Brashear notified the relieving trainmaster Jessie Farmer and the PTRA safety and environmental director Kirk Higbie at 0503 hrs concerning the incident and his actions. Farmer arrived on scene and could not detect any odor or leaks on the car. He attempted to move the car from the siding to the PTRA American Yard for furhter inspection. When the crew coupled Farmer noticed a vapor spray from the manyway cover.  He instructed the crew to tie down the cars and continue with other work. Farmer and Higbie inspected the car and discovered a pinched gasket around the manway cover. Gene Wetmore the loading supervisor from Celanese arrived on scene at approximately 0855 hrs.  Mr. Wetmore removed the pinched gasket and inserted a new gasket. He tightened the bolts and sealed the car at 0920 hrs. There was no evidence of product on the car or ground. The scene was cleared at 0925 hrs.
column169: Kirk Higbie notified David Anderson at BASF concerning the incident and cause. Anderson stated that he would be reviewing the incident with his loading crews to ensure they install the gaskets correctly and tighten the manway bolts properly.

column168: Trailer #7018 was loaded with A-6 and proceeded to the gate.  The gate guard noticed a very small wet spot under the trailer. Upon inspection by the Shift Supervisor and 2 different Qulaity drivers, it was determined that the trailer was potentially leaking from the vessel under the insulation.  The trailer had been at the truck turnaround and a small spot was found there as well.  The 2 wet spots at the turnaround and the gate were covered with absorbent and cleaned up.  The trailer was returned to the loading rack and a second trailer was brought in from Quality and the material was transloaded into the new trailer.    The trailer is only 3 years old and they did find a crack in  the barrel once they got it apart at the repair shop.  They have made  the repairs and then pressured the tank back up and let it sit for the  weekend.  When they came back on Monday, the pressure was still holding  after 48 hours so we will be returning it back to service.

column168: Tank Car PLCX 224305 was discovered leaking from the vacuum breaker by FRA Haz Mat Inspection Doug Johnson during a routine inspection at the Port Terminal Railroad American Yard.  M&M Environmental Protection responded to the incident and determined that the o-ring on the vacuum breaker had rolled out of its seat and pinched in the vacuum breaker allowing product to bypass the vacuum breaker as it sloshed inside the tank. The most likely explanation for the o-ring to come out of the seat was due to an improper inspection and/or test of the vacuum breaker at the shipper facility by using excessive force (using foot or the like) to test the breaker. Had the breaker been tested by slowly and smoothly pressing on the breaker the o-ring most likely would not have been affected.  M&M replaced the o-ring and cleaned the product off of the tank car body. There was no product released to the ground.
column169: Improved training and/or inspection procedures at the shipper facility would have prevent this incident and therefore are recommended at this time.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was enroute from the shipper's location to the intended waste management facility. During this process, it was discovered that one container had a small pinhole leak in the body of the container allowing approximately 8 ounces of material to escape from the container onto the contained transfer area.  Facility personnel immedialtey placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum along with the ansorbent material used to collect the released material.  This container was then secured and sent for disposal to the intended facility.

column168: The incident occurred on 5/09/09 at approximately 18:30. Train #107 south bound with an estimated speed of 45mph derailed at MP 60.5 between latitude N29 33’ 59.5” longitude W81 17’ 5.7” and N29 33’ 58.1” longitude W81 17’ &0”. The reason for the derailment is under investigation.   The result of the derailment caused a hazardous material released to the environment. Rail tanker Tl1.X 110210 laded with 17,800 gallons of hydrochloric acid at 38% concentration was punctured on the lower 81 corner. The hole was approximately 6”x 6”. The release of acid to the environment was estimated at 16,800 gallons. The acid soaked into the surrounding soils by the rail car and in a naturally occurring depressed low laying area. The remaining acid was salvaged and sold to Sun Belt Chemicals.   The package failure was a heavy impact from another rail car striking the lower B left end of the tank car and puncturing a 6”x6” hole in the shell. The duration for the release was estimated at 6 to 18 hours. The first responders (Flagler County, St. Johns County (lead), and Duval) established control of isolation, observation, and no evacuation. The first responders made attempts to control the leak and were deterred by heavy vegetation and the position of the acid car in the matrix of derailed cars. The second attempt was made by SWS Environmental (FEC Railway’s Emergency Contractor) and the counties first responders the morning of May l0’. At this point, it was determined that a significant released occurred. The final ER and remedial actions followed with assistance from FDEP and the USEPA. The site was secured for corrective action on Monday 5/11/09 <>8:00.
column169: No suggestions at this time

column168: On 5/18/2009 at approximately 7:30 PM CST, an ammonia odor was reported to the Longview Fire Department.   This report of a leak was from 3302 South Eastman Road, in Longview TX.  When the HazMat team arrived there they found a small vapor leak at the back of an Airgas ammonia trailer.  The leak appeared to be coming from a 1” globe valve at the back of the trailer.  After donning the proper gear, a crew went into the hot zone where they found a small leak coming from a vapor valve at the rear of the trailer.  The valve was tightened and the leak stopped.   The total time of the incident from the time of the 1st report to the time the vapor leak was controlled was approximately 2 hours.  Because of the nature of the chemical involved and the close proximity of a restaurant, the patrons and workers were evacuated from this restaurant, for precautionary measures. The duration of the evacuation was a total of about 1 hour.  According to the HazMat team that responded approximately 5 pounds of ammonia was released to the atmosphere and no clean up was necessary.  No injuries or illness were reported.
column169: We have review all applicable training with the Airgas driver involved with this incident.  The training included, but was not limited to, Safe Operating Procedure and Post Trip Inspection training.

column168: On 05/26/2009 at 17:00 hrs., FRA Inspector Joel Roberts, in the CSXT Parsons Yard discovered GATX 90477, a loaded tank car of Hexamethylenediamine Solution with dried product spilled within the protective dome area and not able to determine where the leak originated from.The car was isolated and the shipper, Invista, was contacted via CHEMTREC (#05262009052600181).  The OEPA was notified at 17:40 hrs., and a follow-up call was made at 18:00 hrs.  Invista used an in-house response contractor that was dispatched to the scene and found the vacuum relief valve dust cover was missing and there was crystalized product on the inside of the protective housing . Contractor personnel could not replace the vacuum relief device dust cover but did decontaminate the car and performed a pressure test to ensure there were no leaks. An FRA movement approval was obtained by the customer and the car was released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 662  NARRI Score 2(5+3+1) X (2+0) = 36

column168: 2 large cylinders of Hydrogen Chloride, Anhydrous were shipped on their side, in frames, nose to nose. The valve caps were making contact with each other because of vibration enroute. Trailer was immediately pulled from dock and moved downwind from facility at a distance of roughly 100 meters. column169: SECURE FREIGHT TO PREVENT MOVEMENT DURING TRANSIT.  TOTES CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND/OR CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND/OR DUNNAGE. USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.

column169: CHECK HAZARDOUS TOTES AND MAKE SURE LIDS ARE TIGHTLY SECURED AND READY TO RIDE.  BETTER SECUREMENT OF CAP, BUNGS OR LIDS ON DRUMS. THE SEAMS ON THE PACKAGING MUST BE ABLE TO HOLD LIQUID WITHOUT LEAKING OUT.  THE DURABILITY OF A DRUM, PAIL, BAG AND/OR TOTE MUST BE ABLE TO MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION.  IMPORTANT THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE.  TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFELY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER PACKAGING, MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED.  DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT. PACKAGING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN!

column168: Jet Star, Inc. received the order for diesel fuel from Marathon stating that the storage tank was larger than its actual size. The driver was not able to manually stick the tank to determine if the tank had proper ullage.The consignee verbally confirmed that the load would fit in the storage tank and gave the keys to unlock the tank to the driver authorizing off-loading. The storage tank 90% alarm and 95% shutdown both failed causing the tank to overfill. Upon spillage the driver immediately shut down the pump and began the spill cleanup with oil sorbents both pads and rolls. Driver then notified consignee representative of spill. Alocal Haz-Mat clean up company was notified and responded to complete clean up of the spilled diesel fuel.The paved surface was cleaned and less than 1 drum of dirt was removed. Oil barrier dyke was placed in the drainage ditch in the case of any run off.
column169: Jet Star, Inc. has retrained the driver in the gauging of tanks and the reading of the volume charts in the determination of proper ullage. Marathon has been notified that the tank size on the order is incorrect and requires changing. The consignee Ruan is aware of the overfill protection failures and should have them repaired. Jet Star, Inc. will not deliver fuel without visible conformation from the consignee that proper ullage exists and have authorization to off-load.

column168: A van trailer parked at the Clean Harbors temporary storage lot was observed during a routine yard check to have a wet spot underneath it. The supervisor was immediately notified and he called the emergency response team who quickly responded.  The appropriate PPE was donned and the source of the leak was identified as coming from a closed head UN 1H1 polyethylene drum.  The emergency reposne crew immedialtey palced the compromised container into a suitable salavage drum.  IN addition, a suitable absorbent material was used to absorned all free liquids and this material along with all disposabel personel protective equipment and decontamination materials were containerized and sent for disposal to a fully licensed waste management facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, there was no evidence of damage or leaking.  At the conclusion of the spill response activity, it was determined that the container developed a small crack during the rigors of transprotation.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver has been reinstructed to take all necessary steps to inspect containers prior to acceptance and to take those steps necessary to either over pack or transfer material to a suitable alternate container should a drum show evidnce osf suspect integrity.  In additon, the shipper was advised of the situation and was advised to ensure all containers are in shippable condition before releasing them for transport.

column168: DRIVER STATEMENT: Using the truck hose on 68-618 I connected up to and delivered trailer compartment #3, then switched the hose to the #1 compartment on the truck. I then opened the valve; went and checked the fill box and went to the trailer to switch from Supreme Product to Mid-Grade product. As I was doing this, I heard a strong fluid flowing sound. I turned around and saw product flowing out of the discharge valve on the truck. I ran back and closed the valve, immediately broke out the spill kit and used it on the spilled product. I contacted the terminal for assistance, telephoned the Fire Department and shut down the station. Upon inspection of the fitting and hose it appeared that the banding material was loose and not fitting properly which resulted in hose being pushed off the fitting due to the pressure of the product flow, resulting in the spill. The Fire Department responded within 5 minutes, and inspected the scene. Fire Department personnel stated they had no concerns and departed the scene. The Fire Department contacted public works. Public works personnel waited for a supervisor to arrive at the scene. Terminal Manager arrived at scene discussed with public works personnel, solutions and actions to be taken. Public works personnel will return to scene later this afternoon to ensure proper clean up was completed. Terminal Manger contacted environmental clean up personnel, en route when terminal manger left the scene. Approximately 30 gallons of RUL was released to the ground. A minimal amount made its way into the storm water drain adjacent to the delivery area but was contained in the basin. Some product migrated into the mud around the basin and will be removed by the environmental company upon their arrival.
column169: Ensure that all hose couplings are secure prior to making any delivery. MAke sure that each hose has 2 clamps holding hose to ferrule.

column168: ON 5/24/09 WHILE OFF-LOADING A ULD THAT WAS TENDERED AS HOUSEHOLD/PERSONAL GOODS FROM AN OGG INBOUND FLIGHT AND POSITIONING IT FOR LOADING TO A KOA OUT-BOUND FLIGHT.  HNL AGENTS DISCOVERED WHAT APPEARED TO BE DANGEROUS GOODS IN THE ULD.  THE OFF-LOADING AGENT NOTICED A (GARDEN) TILLER UP AGAINST THE SIDE OF THE UL, IDENTIFIED IT AS A POSSIBLE DANGEROUS GOOD AND NOTICED THE ABSENCE OF HAZMAT LABELS ON THE CONTAINER.  UPON FURTHER CHECKING OF THE TILLER THE AGENT FOUND THAT THE TANK HAD FUEL (GAS) IN IT.  AS THE SHIPMENT WAS OUT-BOUND FOR KOA THE AGENT SECURED THE ULD AND NOTIFIED THE OFFICE TO HAVE THE AIR WAYBILL PULLED TO DETERMINE IF DANGEROUS GOODS HAS BEEN DECLARED AT THE TIME THE SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED.  THE SHIPPER HAD SIGNED THE AIR WAY BILL CERTIFYING THAT THE SHIPMENT DID NOT CONTAIN DANGEROUS GOODS.  (A COPY OF THE AIR WAY BILL IS ATTACHED).  THE TILLER WAS REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINER AND SECURED IN THE HNL CARGO FACILITY WAREHOUSE.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS THAT HAD BEEN TENDERED.
column169: The actions taken to prevent recurrence of the incident reported above were to distribute to all stations a bulletin,regarding the undeclared dangerous goods, to be used in agent shift briefings to heighten acceptance awareness.The issuance of periodic reminders (bulletins) regarding agent vigilance and awareness in acceptance and processing of dangerous goods shipments. The accepting agent was counseled and disciplined regarding the processing of shipments, awareness of dangerous goods, and reviewed the annual dangerous goods training materials paying specific attention to acceptance procedures. We are working with our internal training department on developing an dangerous goods awareness program for shippers.

(A)A BNSF train operating on main track derailed 8 railcars including four hazardous material ladened covered hoppers. The cause of this derailment is under investigation. Covered hopper PLCX 21448 (AAR Car Kind C113) derailed on its side with some of the top hatchways opening spilling a portion of its contents. PLCX 21448 also incurred compromising damage to the B-end and middle bottom hopper outlets. The total spillage was estimated at 1/4 of its contents. Ground spillage was vacuumed. This collection of spillage mixed with soil was placed into roll-off containers for disposal profiling and appropriate disposal. The remainder of the contents within PLCX 21448 was transferred into sealed vacuum boxes for truck haulage to the consignee.  (B)A BNSF train operating on main track derailed 8 railcars including four hazardous material ladened covered hoppers. The cause of this derailment is under investigation. Covered hopper PLCX 18923 (AAR Car Kind C113) derailed upright and sustained a horizontal gash across its upper left side sheeting spilling approximately 1/3 of its contents. Ground spillage was vacuumed. This collection of spillage mixed with soil was placed into roll-off containers for disposal profiling and appropriate disposal. The remainder of the contents within PLCX 18923 was transferred into sealed vacuum boxes for truck haulage to the consignee.

A shipment was tendered to Delta Air Cargo for transport from Atlanta to Seattle.  During a physical search of the shipment, eight cases of six 4-packs or Energizer Ultimate Lithium batteries were identified in the shipment.  The interior box was labeled, "Primary lithium batteries - forbiden for transport aboard passenger aircraft." There was no indication of the batteries on the outer packaging or the paperwork.      Batteries were removed and the remaining items in the package was shipped to final destination in Seattle.
column169: Atlanta Cargo Leadership contacted the shipper to inform them that the batteries were removed from their package and that they were not allowed on passenger aircraft. Shipper has been advised that this type of shipment is forbidden on passenger aircraft.  Shipper has also been advised that their paperwork did not accuratly reflect the package contents and has been put on notice.

column168: Load shifted when driver had to brake suddenly, and hard, to avoid striking vehicle that had abruptly pulled in front of him.  The load shift caused a small hole to be torn in the bottom edge of one 15-gallon drum by a protruding object.  The driver heard the load shift and immediately began looking for a safe place to pull over.  The driver exited the freeway and pulled into a large parking area.  Upon exiting the vehicle, the driver saw Muriatic Acid leaking through the bed (front side) of the cargo area of the vehicle to the ground.  The driver contacted emergency personnel (city fire/hazmat) who arrived on scene within approximately 10 minutes.  The city hazmat team applied Soda Ash to the spilled Muriatic Acid which both neutralized and contained the material.  A private hazmat response team, dispatched by Leslie''s, arrived on scene approximately 1.5 hours after the incident to perform clean up.
column169: Leslie''s is reviewing current loading, securement and training practices for the safe transport of hazardous materials.  It is anticipated that the review process will lead to changes in hazardous materials loading, securement and/or training methods in an effort to prevent a recurrence.

column168: Lemont operates a bulk organic chemical storage facility and about 2:25 p.m.; while transferring perchloroethylene from an above ground storage tank into a tanker truck, the IMTT operator inadvertently transferred the material into the truck top manway without closing the rear tanker truck bottom valve. Approximately 46 gallons of perchloroethlene exited the tanker truck bottom valve and spilled into a truck loading concrete containment dike. The facility operators immediately notified the facility management and the Environmental manager. The employees donned personal protective equipment and obtained spill response cleanup material while the Environmental Manager made the notifications to the National Response Center and the Illinois EPA (IEMA)., The spilled material was recovered using spill pads and absorbent material and placed into drums for shipment off site as a hazardous waste.
column169: Preventative actions involved additional training on spill response procedures on May 30, 2009 with all operators and terminal supervisors. The particular employee involved in the incident will be re-trained on loading/unloading operating procedures by his supervisor; appropriate disciplinary procedures was administered which included time-off.

column168: Vehicle #1 = Heritage Transport, LLC            Vehicle #2 = Pan Handle Eastern Pipeline Company                              At approximately 1:30 PM. on May 27, 2009 vehicle #1 operated by Heritage Transport, LLC was traveling northbound on US 231 in Putnam County, Indiana. Vehicle #2 operated by Pan Handle Eastern Pipeline Company backed into traffic from a driveway in front of the Heritage Transport vehicle.  Vehicle #1 slowed down to allow Vehicle #2 into traffic.  Vehicle #2 continued northbound on US 231 in front of Vehicle #1.  A short distance later Vehicle #2 turned on the turn signal to indicate a right hand turn.  The driver of Vehicle #1 began to slow down to approximately 45 mph when he saw the driver's intention of turning right.  As the driver of Vehicle #2 began the righthand turn the driver changed position and then made a U-turn in front of Vehicle #1.  In an effort to avoid Vehicle #2, the driver of Vehicle #1 moved to the left lane but was unable to avoid hitting Vehicle #2.  Vehicle #1 hit the left frontdoor jam of Vehicle #2 and both vehicles ended up in the ditch on the west side of US 231.  Vehicle #1 was carrying an intermodal container that contained 19,940 k of UN3432, Polychlorinated Biphenyls, Solid, Mixture, 9, PGII (PCB Remediation Waste, Sediment/Soil). After the vehicle came to a rest in the ditch, it was sitting at a 45 degree angle. See Attachment F.  Approximately 10 pounds of material were released from the intermodal container.  Continued on page 2, attached.~

column169: DOCK EMPLOYEES NEED TO BE TRAINED TO USE CAUTION WHEN LOADING DRUMS AND OTHER FREIGHT AROUND DRUMS.  RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT.  WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS, OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS.  FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OF FROKLIFT.  DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS!  PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

column168: On 05/07/2009 a shipment of reusable class 4G fiberboard boxes were shipped back to a supplier.  Discovered inside one of the perceived empty boxes was a single Transfer Charge UN0410 Detonation Fuse with protective features.  The single unit has a net explosive weight of 0.004 Ibs and a shipping classification of 1.4D.  The unit was inadvertently left in the box and not seen during preparation of the empty box for return to the supplier for re-use.  The box was shipped as an empty status via FedEx Freight.
column169: Immediate Action: A triple verification of all outbound shipments put into place to prevent reoccurrence while long-term corrective actions are put in place and effectiveness evaluated. The triple verification process includes a shipping, management and                                                      Corrective actions: 1. Additional training to be provided on the procedure to ensure boxes are completely empty.   2. A requirement to have the boxes completely emptied of all material including packing material to validate the "empty" box status.    3. Additional training will be provided on internal inventory controls.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: On May 22nd at approximately 5:25 pm Reliable Tank Line was traveling north on US 221 in Rutherford County when another vehicle operated by Carrie Elizabeth Bridwell ran through a stop sign and drove into the path of Reliable Tank Line.  After the impact the tanker went out of control and overturned several times.  The transport truck and trailer came to rest on its side facing northeast across the roadway.  The cause of the dicharge was due to the trailer striking the roadway.  This caused a tear or rip in the rear portion (right side) of the trailer.  The discharge occurred after the accident.  The discharge was reported by an unknow person or passerby to the wreck scene.  Emergency crews were on the scene at approximately 5:50 pm to start to migated the spill.  The estimated time of the leak was approximatley 15 to 20 minutes.  Due to the size of the tear the product was able to flow with out restriction.  The size of the tear was approximately 8 to 12 inches.
column169: This unfortunate incident was due to no fault of Reliable Tank Line, LLC.  The incident was non-preventable since actions of others can not be controlled.  Reliable Tank Line driver did not receive any citations.  The other party was cited for failure to stop at a signal/posted stop sign.

column168: Truck was traveling westbound on Hwy I-76 in Pennsylvania near mile marker 4 when the truck struck the northside guardrail.  The driver was unable to turn the truck back onto the roadway.  The truck broke through the guardrail and traveled down the embankment coming to rest on its driver's side.  The front compartment (1) was gashed near the midpoint and approximately 1/2 of the gasoline in that compartment leaked out.  On the rear compartment (4) of the trailer the top dome lid sprung partway open releasing approximately 1/2 of the gasoline in that compartment.  Compartments 2 and 3 held and contained all of the gasoline they contained.  Since this incident occured on the Pennsylvania Turnpike, McCutheon Enterprises was called out to contain and clean up the spill.  According to McCutcheon Enterprises, the plan by the Pennsylvania DEP is to use absorbent to soak up the gasoline.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: ARNOLD NAVARRO WAS ON HIS WAY BACK FROM THE BIG SPRING ALON REFINERY WHERE HE HAD PICKED UP A LOAD (7300 GALS OF DIESEL) FOR THE UNITED FUEL & ENERGY CORP. ODESSA BULK PLANT.  HE WAS WEST BOUND ON INTERSTATE 20 AND FELL SLEEP AROUND MILE MAKER 126 (TWO MILES WEST OF HYS 1788) CAUSING HIM TO LOSE CONTROL OF THE TRUCK AND TURN IT OVER, CAUSING A 2485 GALLON DIESEL SPILL.  HE WAS TAKEN TO MIDLAND MEDICAL CENTER IN MIDLAND, TX ALONG WITH HIS TWO KIDS THAT HE HAD ON TRUCK WITH HIM.  HAZMAT OF TEXAS AND TALON LPE WERE CALLED OUT TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT,.   HAZMAT OF TEXAS RESPONDED WITH FOUR BELLY DUMP TRUCKS AND A LOADER TO TAKE 17 TRUCK LOADS OR APPROXIMATELY 374 YARDS OF CONTAMINATED DIRT TO CHARTER WASTE.  THE CONTAMINATED AREA WAS 16' X 100' X 6' DEEP.  SPILL WAS REPORTED TO THE TEXAS COMMISSION ON ENVIROMENTAL QUANTITY AND SIX SOILS SAMPLES WERE TAKEN FROM THE CONTAMINATED AREA FOR CLEAN UP REPORT.

column168: Package arrived as part of UPS delivery.Package was marked as aircraft oil.When box was opened,another box was inside that was completely sataurated and falling apart from battery acid from an unsealed aircraft battery that was inside the inner box.The package was marked with return label address SMP LTD 3422 Old Capital TRL# 700 Wilmington,DE 19808.UPS tracking #K1201844914 shows the package shipped from Griffin,GA on 5/1/09 and arrived at this facility on 5/5/09.Package did not have any hazardous material labeling on it.The battery was indentfied by part number and serial number on it to an invoice as being sold to Ron Anderson for a Cessna T210,registration number N722EL.The FAA registry shows the plane as being sold to SMP LTD with the owner address as 31 Teal CT Locust Grove,GA 30248-2423.This address is listed on public records as the home of Ron Anderson the owner of SMP LTD.
column169: Battery should not have been shipped wet.New batteries are shipped dry,with the battery acid shipped seperatly in sealed quart containers.
